      "span_text": "Two principle approaches for solar water splitting have been advocated: the non-monolithic approach, where photovoltaic light harvesting and electrolytic water splitting are spatially separated, or monolithically integrated devices, which are fully immersed into the electrolytes. The former one avoids issues associated with the semiconductor-electrolyte contact, such as the challenge to employ heterogeneous catalysts with low light absorption 10 and photocorrosion, but necessitates a second technology line 11 . Whereas with the former approach, STH efficiencies of up to 18% have been achieved [CITATION_1] 13 , the benchmark for monolithic water splitting is at 12.4% STH for 11 suns illumination, and achieving simultaneously efficiency and stability remains an issue 14 ."
